To fix the `IndexOutOfBoundsException` errors in your test cases, you need to make sure that the array index you are accessing is within the bounds of the array. Here is the updated code for the `parseWithValidJsonFieldAndInvalidArrayIndexInSrcMap` and `parseWithValidJsonFieldButInvalidArrayIndex` test cases:

```java
// Test case for parsing with valid JSON field and invalid array index in src map
@Test
public void parseWithValidJsonFieldAndInvalidArrayIndexInSrcMap() {
    // Create the JSON input with an invalid array index
    String input = "{\"src\":[\"value1\"]}";

    // Parse the JSON input
    Map<String, Object> result = JSONParser.parse(input);

    // Verify that the result map is not null
    assertNotNull(result);

    // Verify that the result map does not contain the invalid array index
    assertTrue(result.containsKey("src"));
    assertTrue(result.get("src") instanceof String);
    assertEquals("value1", result.get("src"));
}

// Test case for parsing with valid JSON field but invalid array index
@Test
public void parseWithValidJsonFieldButInvalidArrayIndex() {
    // Create the JSON input with an invalid array index
    String input = "{\"array\":[\"value1\",\"value2\"]}";

    // Parse the JSON input
    Map<String, Object> result = JSONParser.parse(input);

    // Verify that the result map is not null
    assertNotNull(result);

    // Verify that the result map contains the array field
    assertTrue(result.containsKey("array"));
    assertTrue(result.get("array") instanceof String);
    assertEquals("value1", result.get("array"));
}
```

In the first test case, `parseWithValidJsonFieldAndInvalidArrayIndexInSrcMap`, the input JSON contains an array with a single element. Therefore, accessing index 2 will throw an `IndexOutOfBoundsException`. In the second test case, `parseWithValidJsonFieldButInvalidArrayIndex`, the input JSON contains an array with two elements, so accessing index 2 will also throw an `IndexOutOfBoundsException`.

